---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import source from "../../examples/reliability-policy.dcl?raw";
import { playgroundExamplePath } from "../../lib/playground/links";

const frontmatter = {
  title: "How Do I Define Reliability Policies?",
  description: "Attach reliability policy to the semantic boundary it governs.",
};
---

<DocsLayout frontmatter={frontmatter}>
  <h1>How Do I Define Reliability Policies?</h1>
  <p>
    Reliability policy expresses operational intent in the language. Attach it to
    the boundary that needs the guarantee: a capability, effect, outcome, event,
    or lifecycle.
  </p>

  <h2>Attach Retry To An Idempotent Boundary</h2>
  <p>
    The compiler requires retry semantics to be paired with idempotency for the
    governed effect. That keeps the model honest about whether retrying is safe.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock title="reliability-policy.dcl" code={source} />
  <p class="inline-actions">
    <a class="button secondary" href={playgroundExamplePath("reliability-policy")}>Open in Playground</a>
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
